[{"id":"VR799441","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div>Which of the following correctly indicates the resulting motion of the electron and provides a valid justification?</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR799441_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows parts of three equipotential lines and the corresponding electric field vectors. The equipotential lines are labeled, from left to right, V sub A, V sub B, and V sub C. Each equipotential line is the arc of a circle, with all three circles concentric. The radius of curvature of V sub A is greater than that of V sub B, which is greater than that of V sub C. Three electric field vectors are shown, on and perpendicular to, each of the equipotential lines. The field vectors all point toward the common center of the circular arcs of the equipotential lines. The field vectors on V sub C are longer than those on V sub B, which are longer than those on V sub A. Point P is indicated about halfway vertically along the V sub B equipotential line.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR799441.g05.svg\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">An electric field <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"vector E\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"vector E\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"> <mover accent=\"true\"> <mi>E</mi> <mo>â†’</mo> </mover> </mstyle> </math></span></span> within a region of space is represented by the arrows shown in the figure. The dashed-line curves represent equipotential lines for three electric potentials, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub A\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"V sub A\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mtext>A</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub B\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"V sub B\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mtext>B</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub C\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"V sub C\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mtext>C</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span>. An electron is released from rest at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"P\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> on the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub B\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"V sub B\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mtext>B</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> equipotential.</p>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electron will move toward the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub C\"><math alttext=\"V sub C\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mtext>C</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> equipotential because electrons move toward stronger electric fields.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electron will move toward the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub C\"><math alttext=\"V sub C\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mtext>C</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> equipotential because electrons experience an electric force in the direction of the electric field.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electron will move toward the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub A\"><math alttext=\"V sub A\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mtext>A</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> equipotential because electrons move toward lower electric potentials.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electron will move toward the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub A\"><math alttext=\"V sub A\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mtext>A</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> equipotential because electrons always accelerate toward higher potential.</p>"],"answer":3}]